Vintage illustration style: A 1960s-era rotary telephone transforming and fragmenting into dozens of sleek, geometric smartphone shapes that scatter outward in a dynamic spiral pattern. The phones decrease in size as they move toward the edges, suggesting infinite variety. The color palette features warm amber, burnt orange, and cream tones with subtle paper texture. The central rotary phone is rendered in detailed cross-hatching while the emerging smartphones become increasingly simplified silhouettes. Scattered between the devices are tangled copper wires morphing into wireless signal waves depicted as elegant curved lines. The composition suggests evolution and growing complexity, with small architectural blueprints and circuit patterns faintly visible in the background, representing the underlying systems. No text or labels anywhere in the image.
